  "prompt": "Why do I have black lines on my teeth?",
  "response": "Black lines on your teeth can be caused by several factors:\n\n1. **Tartar Build-up**: Accumulation of plaque and tartar along the gum line can lead to discoloration. Tartar, especially when it hardens, can appear dark or black over time.\n\n2. **Staining from Food and Beverages**: Certain foods and drinks, especially those rich in tannins or pigments (like red wine, coffee, tea, and certain berries), can stain your teeth and create dark lines.\n\n3. **Tooth Decay**: Cavities can sometimes present as dark spots or lines. If decay is present, it's important to see a dentist.\n\n4. **Dental Restorations**: If you have any dental work, such as fillings or crowns, the materials used may discolor over time, leading to black lines around them.\n\n5. **Medication or Medical Conditions**: Some medications and health conditions can lead to discoloration of teeth. For example, certain antibiotics (like tetracycline) or excessive fluoride can cause darkening.\n\n6. **Genetics and Age**: Natural changes in enamel and dentin as we age can also lead to changes in the appearance of teeth.\n\nIf you notice black lines on your teeth, it's a good idea to consult with a dentist for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment. Regular dental check-ups can help prevent and manage these issues effectively.",
